The late International Pentcost Holiness Church (IPHC) leader Glayton Modise's son Leonard has been accused of putting the EFF's land expropriation without compensation policy in action on a plot owned by a small property developer next to the church's headquarters of Silo in Zuurbekom, south of Joburg. West Rand businessman Sello Mogodiri claimed that Leonard grabbed his land, that he estimates to be worth R1.2m, to expand his agricultural project without his permission. Mogodiri said Modise sent his congregants to occupy his plot, located next to the church, in September last year. TO READ MORE ON THIS STORY GET A COPY OF TODAY'S SUNDAY WORLD